                              speed up the decoding process.
@endnode

@node "Intro" "Introduction"
@{i}@{u}Introduction@{ui}@{uu}

 PhoneSpell is a short little program which tries to decode a given phone
 number into words or encode a given word into a number.  Decode is useful
 with an existing phone number to find any phases that may be used instead
 of the number.  Encoding is used when you are getting a new number.  You
 usually cannot control the exchange part of the number you receive but
 the phone company will allow you to pick the other digits if they are
 available.  A few @{"example numbers" link "examples" 0} are given to help illustrate its usage.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@{i}@{u}Installation@{ui}@{uu}

 To install PhoneSpell just copy the complete PhoneSpell directory to wherever
you want.
@endnode

@node "Layout" " Layout"
@{i}@{u}Layout@{ui}@{uu}

 Click @{"here" system "sys:utilities/multiview  images/main.iff"} to view the programs gui.

 Lister     - Display the results of the process in various forms.

 Phone      - The number you would like decoded or the phase to be encoded,
              depending upon the setting of the Decode/Encode gadget.

 Time Taken - Displays the time the selected process took, in seconds, to
              complete.  Note that the process used will not be accurate
              if ram is chosen and the dictionary is not already in ram.
              This is because of the simple method used to calculate the
              time.  A more accurate method could have been used but
              the amount of additional code needed doesn't justify it.
              For most numbers, the time difference between using ram
              or disk is just a second or two.

 Word Found - How many words were found for the given number.

 ListSelector - There are five lists to choose from when in Decode mode and
                one for the Encode mode:

                Phone  - All of the words found are listed in alphabetical
                         order.
                Suffix - All of the words associated with the first three
                         numbers.
                Prefix - All of the words associated with the last four
                         numbers.
                Edited - The program attempts to put the words into some sort
                         of phase.  Some phases may not be usable.  For
                         instance, if a phase like "calling me" is found it
                         is too long to use.  It is included since the user
                         may want to abbreviate it to something like "call
                         me."  When two words share a position, the word
                         overlap will appear in the list.  That is, using the
                         above example, if calling was found to start at
                         digit 0 and me started at digit 5, then the words
                         overlapped at digit 5.  By using the Prefix and
                         Suffix lists the position of each word relative to
                         its corresponding digit can be found.  This will
                         allow the user to decide which parts, if any, apply.
                Matrix - A matrix is displayed to allow a better idea of
                         which letter goes with which position in the number.
                Encode - Displays the number from the given word in encode
                         mode.

 Dictionary Location - Select either Ram or PROGDIR (Disk) for the location
                       of the dictionary.  If Ram is chosen, the program will
                       check for it in ram:t/.  If it isn't found, a
                       requester will pop up asking what you want to do.  If
                       PROGDIR is chosen, the program reads the file from the
                       phonespell/dictionary directory.

 Mode Selector - Selects whether the program is to decode a number into words
                 or encode a word into a number.

 Print - Print the words found.

 Start - Start the program.

 Clear - Clear the lists and string gadgets.

 Exit  - Quit the program.  The dictionary will be removed from Ram:t/ if
         present.
@endnode

